# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2011-colorado-earthquake
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The **1585 Aleutian Islands earthquake** is the presumed source of a tsunami along the Sanriku coast of Japan on 11 June 1585, known only from vague historical accounts and oral traditions.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The event was initially misdated to 1586, which led to it being associated with the deadly earthquakes in Peru and Japan of that year.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] A megathrust earthquake on the Aleutian subduction zone in the North Pacific Ocean was hypothesized as the tsunami's source.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Paleotsunami evidence from shoreline deposits and coral rocks in Hawaii suggest that the 1585 event was a large megathrust earthquake with a moment magnitude (Mw) as large as 9.25.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] In 1586, a legend emerged in Japan describing a wave measuring up to two meters which struck near Tokura village in the Motoyoshi District of Miyagi Prefecture.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Surviving historical accounts from the period are ambiguous or incomplete, which has made it difficult to identify the tsunami's specific origin.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The tsunami was dubbed the "orphan tsunami" or "ghost tsunami" due to the uncertainties regarding the event.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] According to Kenji Satake, a Japanese seismologist, the legend of the 1586 tsunami should be disregarded because it was a false event.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] There was no historical documentation of a tsunami striking the Sanriku coast in that year.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The 8.1 Mw Peru earthquake of 1586 ruptured an estimated 175-kilometre (109 mi) long section of the Peru-Chile megathrust.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Historical descriptions of the tsunami that struck locally in Callao reported two very different heights, 3.7 and 24 metres (12 and 79 ft).
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The latter was determined to be an exaggeration of the tsunami height after much evaluation; a more accurate estimate for the 1586 Peru tsunami is 5 metres (16 ft).
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Further modelling of the Peru tsunami by a group of researchers in 2006 was unsuccessful in accurately matching the historical descriptions of the wave heights in Peru and Japan.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Large tsunamis originating in Chile have been reported in Japan due to the orientation of the tsunami source, but Peru-sourced tsunamis are usually weaker because they are not directed towards Japan, suggesting that the claim of a Peru tsunami causing the 1586 event in Japan is incorrect.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] In another tsunami catalog compiled after the 1933 Sanriku earthquake, the author referenced a 1903 publication which stated that a tsunami occurred on 11 June 1585, or Tensho 13th year, 5th month and 14th day.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Meanwhile, another tsunami event on 18 January 1586, was recorded, possibly associated with the 1586 Tenshō earthquake (ja).
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Because the Tenshō earthquake occurred in 1586, the Sanriku tsunami was incorrectly dated to 1586, coincidentally matching the Peru quake as well.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The Hawaiian Islands have been known to be hit with large, distant-sourced tsunamis and locally sourced megatsunamis.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The last known megatsunami occurred more than 10,000 years ago.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Throughout the Holocene, tsunamis have repeatedly struck the islands leaving behind evidence of inundation in the form of deposits.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Historical legends passed down by the natives have also described tsunamis hitting the island.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] One of these tsunamis struck Kāne'ohe Bay on the island of Oahu.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Archaeological and historical evidences showed that the tsunami occurred sometime between 1040 and 1280 A.D.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] A chant composed between 1500 and 1600 described a tsunami-like event occurring on the western coast of Molokai.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The chant is believed to be the oldest record of a tsunami in Hawaii.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] At least 24 to 40 metres (79 to 131 ft) of slip has been accumulated since the earthquake of 1585 and it is possible for another event of a similar magnitude to occur.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] If a tsunami were generated, it would require just 4.5 hours of travel time to reach the Hawaiian Islands.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] A study of the northwestern coast of Kauaʻi in 2002 discovered evidence of a large tsunami in a layer of buried sand, similar to the tsunami deposits found after the 1946 earthquake.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Earlier in 2001, at Makauwahi Sinkhole in the Makauwahi Cave complex, on the southern coast of Kauaʻi, researchers uncovered a 0.8 to 1-meter layer of deposit during an excavation of the site.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The sinkhole is 30 to 35 meters wide and walls 6 to 25 meters high.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The allochthonous deposit, consisting of stones and fragmented aeolianite were sourced from a distant location, confirming the occurrence of a major tsunami-like event in the Hawaiian Islands.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The state of these boulders, cobbles, gravel, and sand, severely fractured and angular, concluded that they formed during one intense event.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Dating of the deposits presented a time period of 1430–1665 A.D..
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] In a 2014 study of the site led by Rhett Butler, researchers from the University of Hawaiʻi at Mānoa, National Tropical Botanical Garden and Pacific Tsunami Warning Center found the same deposit, 0.8 meters thick.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] They also measured the bottom of the sinkhole at 7.2 meters above the mean sea level, and location of the sinkhole 100 meters from the coast.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The deposit volume is also estimated to be 600 cubic meters.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Based on the location in which the deposit was found, the tsunami must be a very significant event.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The layer deposited in the sinkhole was sourced by a tsunami much larger than anything generated by the largest Pacific earthquakes.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The largest run-up height in modern times was from the 1960 Valdivia earthquake which tsunami run-up measured 3 meters.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] None of the recent tsunamis have been able to reach and inundate the Makauwahi Sinkhole, which lies 7.2 meters above sea level at a distance of 100 meters from the shore.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Further research in 2017 revisited the sinkhole to radiocarbon date plant materials in the deposit and found that the tsunami inundation occurred between 1425 and 1660 A.D.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Together with the required tsunami run-up heights, the tsunami may have been associated with the misdated Sanriku tsunami of 1586.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The Sanriku orphan tsunami may have been associated with deposited materials in near Sendai City, Miyagi, which could not be explained by nearby earthquakes.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Inscriptions on a monument at Tokura village said that the tsunami struck the northeastern coast of Japan with a height of 1 to 2 meters.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] There is paleotsunami evidence in nine locations in Oregon, Washington and British Columbia to show that a tsunami occurred near the Cascadia subduction zone prior to the 1700 event.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The next prior event in Cascadia was a less energetic tsunami event inferred to have taken place between 1402 and 1502, with an uncertainty of ± 20 years.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] This rules out Cascadia as the cause of the 1585 tsunami.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Dating of the event however, strongly supported the Aleutian Islands as being the tsunami source.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The closest known historical earthquakes from 1585 to 1586 were the 1604 Arica, 1587 Guayllabamba and 1575 Valdivia earthquakes, which all generated tsunamis along the South American coast.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] However, no tsunamis from these events were ever measured on the Japanese coasts.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Paleotsunami studies on Sedanka Island near Amaknak Island found five large tsunami events before 1957.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] One of these tsunami deposits was found up to one kilometer inland and up to 18 meters above sea level.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] This tsunami event has been dated at 1530–1665 A.D.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The Aleutian Islands lie near a convergent plate boundary where the Pacific plate meets the North American plate.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The location where the plates converge is marked on the ocean floor by the Aleutian Trench.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The Pacific plate dives beneath the North American plate along the Aleutian subduction zone which extends for approximately 4,000 km.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The subduction zone is a large thrust fault capable of generating large megathrust earthquakes, sometimes tsunamigenic.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The 1946 Aleutian Islands earthquake and 1964 Alaska earthquake, measuring 8.6 Mw and 9.2 Mw respectively, are examples of earthquakes on the subduction zone; both resulted in devastating tsunamis.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] In the same 2014 study led by Butler, researchers simulated the tsunami from a 9.25 Mw earthquake in the eastern Aleutian Islands, west of the earthquake rupture.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The rupture area is 100 km by 600 km with an average slip of 35 meters on the megathrust.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Their model was found to be sufficient to inundate the sinkhole.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Along the Pacific Northwest coast, the tsunami measured a maximum of 9 meters while the mean height was 3.5 meters.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The orientation of the megathrust with respect to the Hawaiian Islands allowed for much directivity of the tsunami energy.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The results of the model did not rule out the possibility of other distant tsunami source locations.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1585-aleutian-islands-earthquake] However, such events would have to greatly exceed the fault slip seen in other historically large events.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1638-new-hampshire-earthquake] The **1638 New Hampshire earthquake** struck central New Hampshire on 11 June 1638 (1 June on the Julian calendar).
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1638-new-hampshire-earthquake] It was the first major earthquake to strike New England following the start of European colonization.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1638-new-hampshire-earthquake] Modern analysis places its epicenter somewhere near what is now central New Hampshire, with an estimated magnitude between 6.0 and 7.0 mbLg.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1638-new-hampshire-earthquake] This makes it the largest earthquake on record in New Hampshire and New England, and the second strongest in northeastern North America after the 1663 Charlevoix earthquake.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] The **1663 Charlevoix earthquake** occurred on February 5 in New France (now the Canadian province of Quebec), and was assessed to have a moment magnitude of between 7.3 and 7.9.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] The earthquake occurred at 5:30 p.m. local time and was estimated to have a maximum perceived intensity of X (*Extreme*) on the Mercalli intensity scale.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] The main shock epicentre is suggested to have occurred along the Saint Lawrence River, between the mouth of the Malbaie River on the north and the mouth of the Ouelle River on the south.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] A large portion of eastern North America felt the effects.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] Landslides and underwater sediment slumps were a primary characteristic of the event with much of the destruction occurring near the epicentral region of the St.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] Lawrence estuary and also in the area of the Saguenay Graben.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] The event occurred during the early European settlement of North America and some of the best-recorded first-hand accounts were from Catholic missionaries that were working in the area.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] These records were scrutinized to help determine the scale of damage and estimate the magnitude of the quake in the absence of abundant records from that time period.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] The Charlevoix seismic zone (CSZ) lies along the St.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] Lawrence River, northeast of Quebec City.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] Although eastern Canada has relatively infrequent earthquakes, due to its location away from active plate boundaries, the CSZ is its most active part, with five earthquakes of estimated magnitude of 6 or greater since historical records began.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] Focal mechanisms for earthquakes in this zone are consistent with rupture on both reverse faults and strike-slip faults of varied orientation.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] The main structures of the area are faults of the Saint Lawrence rift system that run parallel to the river, formed during the break-up of the supercontinent Rodinia in the late Neoproterozoic and early Paleozoic.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] The greatest seismicity occurs where the rift is overprinted by a ~300 Ma meteorite impact structure, the Charlevoix impact structure.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] Most CSZ earthquakes have hypocenters within the Grenvillian basement at depths between 7 and 15 km.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] Many of the smaller earthquakes do not appear to be located on the rift faults, but within the volumes of rock between them.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] Larger events lie outside the impact structure and have inferred nodal planes consistent with reactivation of the rift faults.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] The relatively weak impact structure is interpreted to cause a perturbation of the regional stress field, affecting the stability of the rift faults.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] The estimated length of the most active portion of the CSZ was 73 kilometres (45 mi) and the fault area was put at 73 km × 25 km (45 mi × 16 mi).
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] These things together suggest that the Charlevoix earthquake was similar in size to the largest of the New Madrid earthquakes and was at least a magnitude 6.8 event.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] The estimation of the earthquake's intensity was based on the condition of the soil where the damage occurred.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] A lower-magnitude range would be preferred if the soil in the area was soft and loosely compacted and a range based on firm ground or bedrock would be proportionately higher.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] The earthquake was felt sharply in New England, though the date recorded for the event was 26 January 1663, as New England was using the Julian calendar at the time.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] A church record entry made by Reverend S.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] Danforth from Roxbury, Massachusetts (~600 km from the CSZ) indicated the initial shock was felt around 6 pm that evening and several more shocks followed the next morning.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] On the shores of Massachusetts Bay, the tops of chimneys were broken on houses and pewter (a malleable metal alloy) was jarred from shelves.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] This level of damage is consistent with a modified Mercalli intensity of VI though this may have been because the early colonials had the capability of producing only relatively weak mortar.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] Using this MMI value and the distance from the epicenter one can estimate the magnitude of the earthquake using published intensity-attenuation relations.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] In a June 2011 report on the earthquake that was published in the *Bulletin* of the Seismological Society of America, John E.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] Ebel, a professor and researcher at Boston College, used these known relations that apply to earthquakes in northeastern North America and determined the magnitude to be 7.3–7.9.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] Great landslides along the Saint Lawrence, Saint-Maurice, and Batiscan Rivers made these rivers muddy after the shock, with the waters of the St.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] Lawrence being affected for up to one month.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] Near Trois-Rivières several waterfalls were transformed by these landslides, and one waterfall on the St.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] Maurice River near Les Grès was said to have been nearly leveled.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] At Saint-Jean-Vianney, Quebec, there was a large earthflow landslide in a sensitive clay, interpreted to have been caused by the 1663 earthquake.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] In 1971 this was the site of another much smaller earthflow that destroyed 41 houses and killed 31 people.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] Multibeam bathymetry data and high-resolution seismic reflection data acquired in the Saguenay Fjord has been used to identify a series of landslide deposits that were probably triggered by the 1663 earthquake.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] The Saguenay region is the site of a geological graben and has been subject to several natural disasters since the turn of the seventeenth century.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] In 1996 it was the site of the largest flood in 20th-century Canadian history, which led to the investigation of the fjord bottom using bathymetric data to determine slope stability.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] The inhabitants of the land were the Algonquin and Iroquois people as well as several thousand French settlers.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] Religious groups like the Ursulines (a Roman Catholic religious institute for women) and the Augustinians left good records of the event.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] These groups accredited the earthquake to God as a retaliation for disobedience and the sale of alcohol to Indigenous people.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] Some very detailed, though inconsistent, summaries were given by several Jesuits, most notably Jérôme Lalemant who provided relatively reserved written accounts of the strong effects of the earthquake back to his superiors in Europe.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] Lalemant was said to have been a disciplined priest with diverse experience and following his time in Canada was brought back to France to be posted the provincial superior of the Society of Jesus.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] Father Charles Simon, on the other hand, was said to have limited training and some written records of his were not received as readily or without hesitation.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] Father Simon seemed to not be of the same mind as the bulk of the devoted, saying "...the Earthquake was rather a Scheme of Divine Mercy than a scourge of Justice,— especially since, in so great a confusion of affairs and perturbations of the elements, no one lost life or fortune.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] Immediately after the earthquake, the missionaries, once it had become clear that no lives had been lost, regarded the earthquake not only as a timely warning to the population of New France for their sinfulness, but also as a sign of God's protection.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] They described it as "miraculous" rather than a disaster, regarding the date of the earthquake as particularly important, coming on the last day of the carnival, just before Mardi Gras.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] They were pleased to see all the colonists attending church regularly in the following days and that even the traffickers in wine and brandy appeared to repent.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1663-charlevoix-earthquake] These effects were short-lived and Lalemant and other missionaries were soon left wishing for another great earthquake to help them in their cause.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] The **1700 Cascadia earthquake** occurred along the Cascadia subduction zone on January 26, 1700, with an estimated moment magnitude of 8.7–9.2.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] The megathrust earthquake involved the Juan de Fuca plate from mid-Vancouver Island, south along the Pacific Northwest coast as far as northern California.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] The plate slipped an average of 20 meters (66 feet) along a fault rupture about 1,000 kilometers (600 miles) long.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] The earthquake caused a tsunami which struck the west coast of North America and the coast of Japan.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] Japanese tsunami records, along with reconstructions of the wave moving across the ocean, put the earthquake at about 9:00 PM Pacific Time on the evening of 26 January 1700.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] The earthquake took place at about 21:00 PT on January 26, 1700 (NS).
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] Although there are no written records for the region from the time, the timing of the earthquake has been inferred from Japanese records of a tsunami that does not correlate with any other Pacific Rim quake.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] The Japanese records exist primarily in the modern-day Iwate Prefecture, in communities such as Tsugaruishi, Miyako (Kuwagasaki) and Ōtsuchi.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] The fact that the waves were recorded as striking Ōtsuchi and Kuwagasaki on the same day and hour helped researchers pinpoint the estimated date, time, and place of origin of the earthquake.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] According to Japanese records, destructive waves hit towns along the Pacific Coast of Japan on the 8th and 9th days of the 12th month of Genroku 12, which would be equivalent to January 27 and 28, 1700.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] Based on the damage reports in Japanese records, the maximum wave heights were estimated to be in the range of 2–5 meters.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] At Kuwagasaki, 13 houses were destroyed by flooding and 20 in a subsequent fire, representing about 10% of all buildings in the town.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] At Ōtsuchi, two buildings and two salt kilns were damaged and some fields and paddies were also flooded.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] At Miho, the village headman observed the waves and warned the villagers to flee to higher ground.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] At Nakaminato, where oceangoing ships unloaded their cargoes to smaller vessels to travel by river to Edo (now Tokyo), a ship carrying 28 metric tons of rice was unable to enter the port due to high waves.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] Later that evening, a storm drove it onto a rocky shore, killing two sailors and destroying the cargo.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] In the Tanabe area, the waves flooded wheat fields, rice paddies, and a storehouse, and ascended the moat of Tanabe Castle.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] As no one in Japan had felt an earthquake before the waves struck, many writers were reluctant to call them a tsunami, with some referring to them as merely high tide or high waves.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] An observer at Kuwagasaki called it a tsunami while the village headman of Miho was puzzled after observing that the waves behaved like a tsunami but no earthquake had been felt in the area.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] This includes both inland stands of trees, such as one on the Copalis River in Washington, and pockets of tree stumps that are now under the ocean surface and become exposed only at low tide.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] Sediment layers in these locations demonstrate a pattern consistent with seismic and tsunami events around this time.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] Core samples from the ocean floor, as well as debris samples from some earthquake-induced landslides in the Pacific Northwest, also support this timing of the event.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] Archaeological research in the region has uncovered evidence of several coastal villages having been flooded and abandoned around 1700.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] It was once conjectured that the Cascadia earthquake may also have been linked to the Bridge of the Gods – Bonneville Slide and the Tseax Cone eruption in British Columbia, Canada.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] However, 21st-century investigations using radiocarbon dating and dendrochronology date the Bonneville landslide to around 1450.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] The contemporary indigenous groups of Cascadia had no known written documentation like that of the Japanese tsunami, but numerous oral traditions describing a great earthquake and inundation exist among indigenous coastal peoples from British Columbia to Northern California.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] These do not specify a date, and not all earthquake stories in the region can be ascribed to the 1700 quake; however, virtually all of the native peoples in the region have at least one traditional story of an event of unmatched destructive power.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] Some of the stories contain temporal clues—such as a time estimate in generations since the event—which suggest a date range in the late 1600s or early 1700s, or which concur with the event's timing in other ways.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] For instance, the Huu-ay-aht legend of a large earthquake and ocean wave devastating their settlements at Pachena Bay places the event on a winter evening shortly after the village's residents had gone to sleep (consistent with the 9:00 PM reconstructed time).
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] Every community on Pachena Bay was wiped out except for Masit on a mountainside 23 metres (75 ft) above sea level.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] The only other Panchena Bay survivor was a young woman named Anacla aq sop, who happened to be staying that day at Kiix-in, located on the less-tsunami-impacted Barkley Sound.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] Makah stories from Washington speak of a great night-time earthquake, of which the only survivors were those who immediately fled inland before the tsunami hit.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] The Quileute people in Washington have a story about a flood so powerful that villagers in their canoes were swept inland all the way to Hood Canal.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] Oral history from southern Oregon describes a large tidal wave that uprooted trees and swept away villages, with people tying their canoes to treetops and some canoes being torn loose and swept away.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] Ethnographic research has focused on a common regional pattern of art and mythology depicting a great battle between a thunderbird and a whale, as well as cultural signifiers such as earthquake-inspired ritual masks and dances.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] The geological record reveals that great earthquakes with moment magnitude 8 or higher occur in the Cascadia subduction zone about every 500 years on average, often accompanied by tsunamis.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] There is evidence of at least 13 events at intervals from about 300 to 900 years with an average of 570–590 years.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] As seen in the 1700 quake, the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake, and the 2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami, subduction zone earthquakes can cause large tsunamis, and many coastal areas in the region have prepared tsunami evacuation plans in anticipation of a possible future Cascadia earthquake.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] However, the major nearby cities, notably Seattle, Portland, Vancouver, Victoria, and Tacoma might be sheltered from the full brunt of a tsunami.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] These cities have many vulnerable structures, especially bridges and unreinforced brick buildings; consequently, most of the damage to the cities would probably be from the earthquake itself.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] One expert asserts that buildings in Seattle are inadequate even to withstand an event of the size of the magnitude 7.9 1906 San Francisco earthquake, let alone a more powerful one.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] Recent findings conclude that the Cascadia subduction zone is more complex and volatile than previously believed.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] In 2010, geologists predicted a 37% chance of a magnitude 8.2+ event within 50 years, and a 10% to 15% chance that the entire Cascadia subduction zone will rupture with a magnitude 9+ event within the same time frame.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] Geologists have also determined the Pacific Northwest is not prepared for such an earthquake.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] The tsunami produced could reach heights of 24 to 30 metres (80 to 100 ft).
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] A 2004 study revealed the potential for relative mean sea level rise (caused by subsidence of coastal land) along the Cascadia subduction zone.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] It postulated that cities on the west coast of Vancouver Island, such as Tofino and Ucluelet, are at risk for a 1-to-2-metre (3 to 7 ft) subsidence relative to mean sea level.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] The confirmation of their oral traditions about a great earthquake has led many indigenous groups in the area to initiate projects to relocate their coastal communities to higher and safer ground in preparation for the predicted next earthquake.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] The Huu-ay-aht People have rebuilt their administration building on a high point in their territory; coastal residents are immediately evacuated to this building whenever a tsunami warning is issued, as an interim measure toward eventually relocating all residents to higher ground.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] The Quileute people secured a land grant from the US government in 2012 to move their settlement inland, both as protection from a future tsunami threat and because of more frequent flooding on the Quillayute River.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] The Shoalwater Bay Indian Tribe also sought federal funding to move their community uphill receiving a FEMA PDM grant to build the first vertical evacuation tower on their coast, completed near the Tokeland Marina in 2022.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] In 2023, Washington scientists reported on a detailed study of a high-pressure and high-temperature seafloor seep, likely on the plate boundary, offshore of Oregon.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] The first seep found on the CSZ, it has been named 'Pythia's Oasis', and may play a role in the regulation of overpressures.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1700-cascadia-earthquake] Some other subduction zones have major earthquakes every 100 to 200 years; the longer interval here may indicate unusually large stress buildup and subsequent unusually large earthquake slip.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] The **1755 Cape Ann earthquake** took place off the coast of the British Province of Massachusetts Bay (present-day Massachusetts) on November 18.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] At between 6.0 and 6.3 on the Richter scale, it remains the largest earthquake in the history of Massachusetts.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] No one was killed, but it damaged hundreds of buildings in Boston and was felt as far north as Nova Scotia and as far south as South Carolina.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] Sailors on a ship more than 200 miles (320 km) offshore felt the quake, and mistook it at first for their ship running aground.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] Many residents of Boston and the surrounding areas attributed the quake to God, and it occasioned a brief increase in religious fervor in the city.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] Modern studies estimate that if a similar quake shook Boston today, it would result in as much as $5 billion in damage and hundreds of deaths.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] Some discussion has revolved around the idea that this may have been a remotely triggered event from the 1755 Lisbon earthquake or its aftershocks.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] The earthquake took place on November 18, 1755, at approximately 4:30 AM local time.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] Future President of the United States John Adams, then staying at his father's house in Braintree, Massachusetts, was awakened by the quake, which impressed him so much that he began a diary that night.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] He wrote that the quake "continued near four minutes" and that "[t]he house seemed to rock and reel and crack as if it would fall in ruins about us." Its epicenter is believed to have been offshore, approximately 24 miles (39 km) east of Cape Ann.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] The quake was felt as far north as Halifax, Nova Scotia, south to the Chesapeake Bay and South Carolina, and from Lake George and Lake Champlain in the northwest to a ship 200 miles (320 km) off the east coast.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] Sailors on the ship reported that the quake was so strong, they had feared that they had run aground.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] The region experienced several aftershocks, the first of which was a little more than an hour after the quake.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] Most of these aftershocks could not be felt in Boston, affecting only the northeastern coast of the colony.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] Modern research has estimated that the quake was between 6.0 and 6.3 on the Richter scale, and the United States Geological Survey lists it as the largest earthquake in the history of Massachusetts.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] Scientists are unclear on the causes of this and other quakes in the northeastern United States.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] There are a number of old faults in the region, but none of them is known still to be active.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] It is possible that the Cape Ann earthquake may have been remotely triggered by a larger earthquake in Lisbon, Portugal, a few weeks prior, although there is not enough evidence to prove that they are linked.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] Boston and Cape Ann were the most heavily damaged.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] In Boston, damage was concentrated in areas of infill near the harbor; infill is less sturdy in earthquakes than solid land.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] From 1,300 to 1,600 chimneys in the city were damaged in some way, the gable ends of some houses collapsed, and a number of roofs were damaged by falling chimneys.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] Stone chimneys and buildings were damaged in Falmouth (present-day Portland, Maine), Springfield, Massachusetts, and New Haven, Connecticut, as well.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] Some church steeples in Boston were damaged, ending up tilted from vertical.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] Stone fencing in rural areas was damaged.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] Observers also reported that several springs dried up, new ones were created, and cracks appeared in the ground near Scituate, Lancaster, and Pembroke.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] In this last town, observers noted water and fine sand coming from the crack.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] Non-structural damage was minor; residents reported damage to china and glassware, and a distiller lost some of his product after a cistern was damaged.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] The Cape Ann earthquake may also have created the first recorded tsunami in United States history.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] Observers in the Leeward Islands nearly 1,000 miles (1,600 km) south of Cape Ann, reported a receding of water followed by a large wave that lifted several boats ashore and left fish floundering on the beach.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] Many Massachusetts residents of the time perceived the quake as punishment from God for immoral behavior.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] In the days after the earthquake, special prayer services were held and civic authorities declared fast days.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] A number of sermons and other writings were published as a consequence, including Jeremiah Newland's *Verses Occasioned by the Earthquakes in the Month of November 1755* and Thomas Prince's *Earthquakes the Works of God and Tokens of his Just Displeasure*.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] Well before 1755, the new rational materialist ideas promulgated by Enlightenment scientists had begun to heavily influence the better-educated citizens of colonial America; therefore not all explanations of the event were theological.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] John Winthrop, a Harvard professor, proposed an alternate explanation having to do with heat and chemical vapors inside the surface of the earth.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] Many of the buildings in modern Boston and its surroundings are built on infill, especially in the Back Bay area, which may be prone to greater shaking and to compaction of the sand and gravel used as fill.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] Many older buildings in the Boston area are masonry, and may collapse completely during a major earthquake.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] A 1990 study by the Massachusetts Emergency Management Agency estimated potential financial losses at between $4 billion and $5 billion, and potential loss of life in the hundreds.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1755-cape-ann-earthquake] As a consequence, the state has updated building codes and zoning laws to require that new construction and additions in vulnerable areas be built to resist earthquakes.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1783-new-jersey-earthquake] (UTC−5), a Mfa 5.3 earthquake occurred in the U.S. state of New Jersey.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1783-new-jersey-earthquake] It was the state's first recorded seismic event.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1783-new-jersey-earthquake] It is estimated that the quake was the largest and strongest that the state has ever recorded.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1783-new-jersey-earthquake] The earthquake caused intensity VII damage on the Mercalli intensity scale.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1783-new-jersey-earthquake] The earthquake is thought to have originated from within the New Jersey Highlands of the Reading Prong, possibly on the 300 km long, 12 km wide Ramapo Fault zone, a structure formed during the Late Triassic during the break-up of Pangaea.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1783-new-jersey-earthquake] The mainshock was part of a sequence that occurred over a span of several hours.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1783-new-jersey-earthquake] A brief foreshock occurred at 9:00 PM on November 29 (02:00 UTC on November 30), and an aftershock five hours later was reported only in New York City and in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1783-new-jersey-earthquake] The main shaking was felt from New Hampshire to Pennsylvania.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1783-new-jersey-earthquake] There are reports and recordings in diaries that suggest that the earthquake was felt in neighboring states.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1783-new-jersey-earthquake] The overall destruction of the quake was not very serious, only ranking as intensity VII damage on the Mercalli intensity scale.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1783-new-jersey-earthquake] The physical damages include dishes thrown off the shelves, people waking up from the shaking, and multiple damaged chimneys.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1783-new-jersey-earthquake] George Washington was visiting New York City at the time to mark the Evacuation Day departure of British forces, and was sleeping at Fraunces Tavern when the earthquake struck, but he was not woken by the tremors.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1783-new-jersey-earthquake] Reports show that the earthquake was felt in Philadelphia, New Haven, and Boston.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1783-new-jersey-earthquake] Diary entries regarding the earthquake were very brief.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1783-new-jersey-earthquake] Many Contemporary newspapers reported on the earthquake.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] The **1811–1812 New Madrid earthquakes** were a series of intense intraplate earthquakes beginning with an initial earthquake of moment magnitude 7.2–8.2 on December 16, 1811, followed by a moment magnitude 7.4 aftershock on the same day.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] Two additional earthquakes of similar magnitude followed in January and February 1812.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] They remain the most powerful earthquakes to hit the contiguous United States east of the Rocky Mountains in recorded history.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] The earthquakes, as well as the seismic zone of their occurrence, were named for the Mississippi River town of New Madrid, then part of the Louisiana Territory and now within the U.S. state of Missouri.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] The epicenters of the earthquakes were located in an area that at the time was at the distant western edge of the American frontier, only sparsely settled by European settlers.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] The 1906 San Francisco earthquake, by comparison, was felt moderately over roughly 6,200 sq mi (16,000 km2).
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] The earthquakes were interpreted by Tecumseh's pan-Indian alliance to mean that Tecumseh and his brother the Prophet must be supported.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] The Shaker diarist Samuel Swan McClelland described the effects of the earthquake on the Shaker settlement at West Union (Busro), Indiana, where the earthquakes contributed to the temporary abandonment of the westernmost Shaker community.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] The underlying cause of the earthquakes is not well understood, but modern faulting seems to be related to an ancient geologic feature buried under the Mississippi River alluvial plain, known as the Reelfoot Rift.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] The New Madrid seismic zone is made up of reactivated faults that formed when what is now North America began to split or rift apart during the breakup of the supercontinent Rodinia in the Neoproterozoic era (about 750 million years ago).
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] Faults were created along the rift, and igneous rocks formed from magma that was being pushed towards the surface.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] The resulting rift system failed to split the plate, but has remained as an aulacogen (a scar or weak zone) deep underground.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] The quakes caused extensive changes to the region's topography.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] Subsidence, uplift, fissures, landslides and riverbank collapses were common.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] Trees were uprooted by the intense shaking.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] Reelfoot Lake was formed in Tennessee by subsidence of 1.5 meters to 6 meters in some places.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] Francis in eastern Arkansas was expanded by subsidence, with sand and coal being ejected from fissures in the adjacent swamps as water levels rose by 8 to 9 meters.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] Waves on the Mississippi River caused boats to wash ashore; river banks rose, sand bars were destroyed, and some islands completely disappeared.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] Sand blows occurred in Missouri, Tennessee, and Arkansas, covering farmland.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] The continuous underlying rock mass, uninterrupted by fractures or faults, conducted the seismic waves from the earthquakes over great distances, with perceptible ground shaking as far away as Canada.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] Intense effects were widely felt in Illinois, Arkansas, Tennessee, Kentucky and Missouri.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] The number of people who died is unknown; as a frontier area, the region was sparsely populated, and communications and records were poor.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] The predominantly wooden buildings resisted collapse, though the intense shaking caused many chimneys to fall, wood structures to crack, and trees to fall on buildings, particularly in the epicentral area during the first earthquake on December 16, 1811.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] Additionally, people drowned when subsided land began to flood.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] Rated at VII on the Mercalli Intensity Scale, the New Madrid earthquakes remain the strongest recorded North American earthquakes east of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] The earthquakes strengthened the Shawnee prophet Tenskwatawa after the defeat at the Battle of Tippecanoe and the destruction of Prophetstown, with local Native Americans seeing it as a vindication of his teachings and of the warnings of his brother Tecumseh.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] Francis River were flooded and abandoned and the Cherokee moved to the Arkansas River valley.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] In recent decades, minor earthquakes have continued.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] The epicenters of over 4,000 earthquakes can be identified from seismic measurements since 1974, originating from the seismic activity of the Reelfoot Rift.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] A United States Geological Survey (USGS) forecast made in 2003 estimated a 7–10% chance of a major earthquake like those of 1811–1812, and a 25–40% chance of a quake of magnitude 6 or greater, within the next 50 years.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/1811-1812-new-madrid-earthquakes] In a report filed in November 2008, the U.S.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/2011-colorado-earthquake] The **2011 Colorado earthquake** occurred on August 22 at 11:46 PM MDT with a moment magnitude of 5.3 and a maximum Mercalli intensity of VII (*Very Strong*).
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/2011-colorado-earthquake] The epicenter of the intraplate earthquake was 10 mi (20 km) west northwest of Trinidad, Colorado, and 180 mi (290 km) south of Denver, according to the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/2011-colorado-earthquake] It was the largest natural earthquake to affect Colorado for more than a hundred years.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/2011-colorado-earthquake] The earthquake occurred as part of a swarm of smaller quakes that started the previous day.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/2011-colorado-earthquake] The last time the Colorado region received a series of earthquakes was in 2001, when about a dozen smaller-sized temblors were recorded.
[src:2011-colorado-earthquake/2011-colorado-earthquake] The shock occurred as a result of normal faulting and was similar in depth, style and location to the events that made up the 2001 swarm.
